3 character string with positional charcters representing Year Month Date (YMD). Values are A  accurate, E  estimate, U  unknown (value=A, E or U) EG. AEU means Year Accurate, Month Estimated and Date Unknown

Describes number of progeny born to dam in a single birth event. values are 0 if the animal is born dead, 1 if the animal is a singleton, 2 if it is one of twins, etc. Positive integer or NULL if unknown

Describes the season (spring/autumn) within the birth year into which animals are categorised. This is most likely derived or calculated from the birth date. As seasons vary around the world (including variations with 2, 4, 6, or 12 cohorts), a cohort number is used to interchange this data.
Known as YearBorn in many systems. Derived from Birth Date where available.
Mob ewe prior to lambing
Mob ewe paost lambing
Describes the status of an animal as recorded in the Provider system at time of data transfer. Usually  'Alive' or 'Dead', but can include other 'status' information such as 'Culled' and 'Sold'.
The gender or sex of the animal. This may be combined with state information to indicate the fertility status of the animal. enumeration: Male or Female. NULL  for unknowns.
Visual assessment of animal's primary or major breed. Known as "Breed" in many systems.

Breed (enumerations) and breed proportion (in terms relative to the Breed Distribution Denominator, “Sixteenths”, “SixtyFourths”, or “Percentage”). A two-dimensional matrix of breed identifiers and the proportion of each breed in the animal (calculated from
its parent’s breed components). SIL currently uses percentages, and the NZ Dairy Databases use 16ths, e.g. F8J8 (Friesian 8, Jersey 8). We
have also seen systems use 64ths.
Describes the basis for the proportion of each breed expressed in the breedDistribution. Enumeration: 16, 64, 100.
Visually assessed colour of the animal
Combines Genus and Species. Genus is capitalised eg "Bos taurus"
Common term for species. Enumeration: Cattle, Deer, Goats, Sheep

Describes the disposal method for an animal that is dead. Values = HomeKill,Disposed at NAIT Location, Meatprocessor-human consumption, Meat Prociessor - per food, Rendering Facility
Typically describes if the animal is Alive, Dead or in Transit. Also known as "Status" in some systems. Reason for Fate should be captured as an observation.

Indicates whether an animal is known to be fertile or note, or whether it has been partly or fully neutered. For instance, a neutered cattle male is a steer, a neutered sheep male is a wether. Females of both species can be spayed. An infertile male by comparison still has testes and responds as a male, and is frequently used as a “teaser”.
Describes if animal is lactating at time of data transfer. Note this may change many time over an animal's life.

Rearing rank is used to indicate the number of progeny reared by the same dam during the same lactation as this has an influence on weights and growth rates. For example, an animal reared as a twin will have a rearing rank of 2. May be Null if unknown, or 0 if born dead.
Describes if the animal is pregnant at the time of data transfer. Note this may change many time over an animal's life.Values = Unknown, Cycling, Not Cycling, Pregnant, Involuting
Date the fate or status last changed.

This specifies the type of parentage that is claimed: Dam (natural dam), ET Recipient Dam, ET Donor (Genetic) Dam, Rearing Dam (reared, but did not give birth to the progeny), Sire (multiple sire records may be recorded, each with its own DNA probability if DNA testing indicates multiple matches) Excluded Sire (unable to confirm the sire, but definitely not this animal).

Documents how parentage was assessed: - Observed (e.g. Dam observed giving birth to progeny)
- Associated (e.g. Dam seen feeding progeny)
- Derived (e.g. Sire derived from mating records)
- DNA (the result of a DNA parentage test)

Calculated degree of probability resulting from dna test analysis. Percentage.
A statistic that predicts the variability in breeding values using the dna parentage. Effectively predicting dnaDataQuality. Percentage.
Age of dam as determined by dna sample.
The number of progeny born to the same dam in the same birth event.

A lamb can have several possible dams and hence could be part of different litter sizes e.g. if assigned to a dam with no other lambs would be a single but if assigned to a different dam might be a twin. The average rearing rank for the lamb is used.
Age is an important effect in breeding value analyses so a birth date is worked out from the size of the foetus at pregnancy scanning and stored as dna birth date.
Same as dnaBirthDate effectively. FP refers to fitted pedigree.
